  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.7724" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <p>John Chinaman’s<note n="1" place="foot"
              type="editorial">John Chinaman was a stock caricature of a Chinese laborer seen in cartoons of the 19th century. Also referenced by Mark Twain and popular American songs of the period. John Chinaman represented, in western society, a typical persona of China. He was typically depicted with a long queue and wearing a coolie hat. American political cartoonist Thomas Nast, who often depicted John Chinaman, created a variant, John Confucius, to represent Chinese political figures“ (<ref
            target="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Chinaman">wikipedia</ref>).</note> Lignum vitae.<note n="2"
            place="foot" type="editorial">Da der Text sauber abgeschrieben und problemlos lesbar ist, wird er (bis auf fremde AnmerkungenI nicht eigens wiedergegeben!</note>
        </p>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
        <pb facs="#IMG.3" n="3"/>
        <pb facs="#IMG.4" n="4"/>
        <p>Anmerkung auf S. 11 The following piece of verse was written by Major Arthur T. Bingham-Wright, and answers admirably (p. 12) the double purpose of describing the uses of the bamboo-tree, and also of illustrating the peculiarities of the strange jargon called Pidgin-English – a language invented in China as a means of communication between English or American and the natives. Pidgin seems to be a Chinese attempt at pronouncing the word „business“ and it certainly is used now for „business“. Pidgin English is in fact, distorted English words arranged according to Chinese order and idiom: </p>
        <p>John Chinaman ….</p>
        <p>1 – 4</p>
        <p>p. 13. 5 – 10</p>
        <pb facs="#IMG.5" n="5"/>
        <pb facs="#IMG.6" n="6"/>
      </div>
      <div corresp="#L.7724" subtype="original" type="appendix" xml:lang="de">
        <pb facs="#IMG.7" n="7"/>
        <dateline>UNION POSTALE UNIVERSELLE AMOY JAN 18 83] </dateline>
        <pb facs="#IMG.8" n="8"/>
        <dateline>Amoy, den 18. Januar 1883.</dateline>
        <opener>Verehrtester Herr Professor!</opener>
        <p>Ihre Postkarte habe ich erhalten u. werde an Herrn v. Möllendorff, Hongkong, sobald derselbe von einer Dienstreise dahin zurückgekehrt sein wird, in Ihrer Angelegenheit schreiben.</p>
        <p>Kennen Sie das Buch: Glossary on subjects connected with the Far East, by Herbert A. Giles – 83<note n="3"
            place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.7589">Herbert Allen Giles, <hi
                  rend="unknown" rendition="#none">A Glossary of reference on subjects connected with the Far East</hi>, Shanghai: Kelly &amp; Walsh, 1883.</ref>
            </bibl>
          </note> und die Zeitschrift China Review Hongkong 6 Hefte jährlich zu 6<hi rendition="#sup">50</hi>?<note
            n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">The China review or notes and queries on the Far East</hi>, Hongkong [u.a.] : Gale Language Learning; 1.1872/73 - 25.1900/01</note>
        </p>
        <p>Vielleicht wären diese Sachen für Sie von Interesse.</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Besten Gruß von Ihrem ergebensten</salute>
          <signed> V<persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1021">Aichberger</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
    </body>
